The TDPL spectra of LCAO:7Eu3+ NPs and CDs(4 wt%)@LCAO:7Eu3+ NCs under 395 nm excitation are displayed in Fig. 5
                           a and c, respectively. Across the temperature range of 300–480 K, the emission spectra maintain consistent peak positions, with the primary emission at 613 nm (5D0→7F2) unaffected by temperature changes. However, the normalized emission intensity decreases as temperature increases, as visualized in the 3D graphs (Fig. 5b and d). At 420 K, the residual PL intensity is measured to be 84.4 % for LCAO:7Eu3+ NPs and 91.5 % for CDs(4 wt%)@LCAO:7Eu3+ NCs (Fig. 5e). These values significantly surpass those of the commercial Sr2Si5N8:Eu2+ phosphor and other reported phosphors (Table 6
                           ) [19,78–82]. This exceptional thermal stability positions CDs(4 wt%)@LCAO:7Eu3+ NCs as a superior candidate for lighting applications compared to conventional materials.

Seeing the seeds germinated at about day 14, we have recorded the chilli plant growth up to 55 days. Every day between day 15 and day 55, the plants growth in both groups is tracked with practical results shown in Fig. 8
                           a. By day 55, w-LED-grown plants exhibited enhanced growth compared to sunlight-grown plants. The w-LED group showed thicker stems, larger leaves, and denser foliage, demonstrating the light's ability to enhance photosynthetic efficiency. It is found that the w-LED lighting with enough red and blue lights can greatly promote the growth of leaves [96]. Quantitative growth data (Table 9
                           ) highlighted the following improvements for w-LED-grown plants compared to sunlight-grown plants: Plant height: 6.17 % increase, Stem diameter: 21.42 % increase, Leaf width: 10.65 % increase (Fig. 8b–d). The ability of plants to use and control light energy is reflected in the content and makeup of photosynthetic pigments, which has a direct impact on the rate at which green plants photosynthesize [97]. One of the photosynthetic pigments, chlorophyll, has the ability to absorb, transmit, and transform light energy. This energy has been recovered by dissociating in an acetone solution. Photosynthetic pigment analysis revealed a significant enhancement in all chlorophyll content (Fig. 8e). The w-LED group showed a 19.50 % increase in total chlorophyll content compared to the sunlight group (Table 10
                           ). The combined red and blue wavelengths of the w-LED promoted the synthesis of photosynthetic pigments, enhancing the plant's photosynthetic rate and overall growth. These findings support the application of the fabricated w-LED as an effective tool for indoor cultivation, particularly in environments with limited access to natural sunlight. The artificial lighting system extended the duration of photosynthetic activity, leading to better plant growth and development.
